ems like the parent-first loading mechanism is prioritizing classes from the java.xml module instead of the jar file, which may lead to a ClassNotFound issue for SecuritySupport, since it's package-private.\\\\n\\\\nGiven that javax.xml.parsers.SecuritySupport might be absent in the modern JDK, I'm wondering if I should force-load jar classes since there’s a sealed module package conflict. I'll need to inspect the build process and check if the xmlParserAPIs jar is actually on the classpath.\\\"},{\\\"type\\\":\\\"summary_text\\\",\\\"text\\\":\\\"**Examining JPMS class loading issues**\\\\n\\\\nIt seems JPMS blocks access to classes in a package owned by a module, as the classloader prioritizes the platform module over the classpath for a package in a named module. I wonder about split packages — a test class in the java.sql package likely won’t load due to restrictions. To address the absence of javax.xml.parsers.SecuritySupport in JDK 21, we might need to use a public API from older versions. A custom ClassLoader could help here, manually defining classes from the jar to navigate these challenges.\\\"},{\\\"type\\\":\\\"summary_text\\\",\\\"text\\\":\\\"**Considering dynamic class loading issues**\\\\n\\\\nI notice that direct class loading from an existing dependency jar may not be natively supported. Tests generally should run natively by default, and dynamic class loading is allowed only when necessary. I’m pondering whether a custom class loader could read bytecodes for SecuritySupport and define the class javax.xml.parsers.SecuritySupport. However, I’m concerned about a potential SecurityException—could defining in the javax package be prohibited? It seems likely that a non-bootstrap class loader could handle defining javax.xml.parsers.\\\"}]}\"}, {\"type\": \"toolCall\", \"id\": \"call_NwzUWX5EFplSJdf10el3bebD|fc_0bb5d39a304e23be0169f8f89341d08194ae6058283c96d807\", \"name\": \"bash\", \"arguments\": {\"command\": \"jshell <<'EOF'\\nvar bytes = java.nio.fil